                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/25080</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chairman of the Pan-American Federation of Labor</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gompers</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-07-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 8, 1921</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your letter of July 7th<note
                        n="64" xml:id="d386fn64">Not printed.</note> in which you quote a telegram
                    received from Mr. Davison, Secretary of the International Association of
                    Machinists, and Mr. John Kelly, who are now in Orizaba, Mexico, and request that
                    a statement be made that the sending of ships to Mexican waters is “not with the
                    object of interfering with the struggle of the workers in Tampico.”</p>
                <p>Permit me to say in reply, that the presence of the ships has nothing whatever to
                    do with labor unions to which Mr. Davison refers in his telegram or with
                    disputes between employers and employees, but is simply a precautionary measure
                    for the purpose of assuring adequate protection to the lives and property of
                    American citizens. It is hoped, of course, that this protection will be accorded
                    by the local authorities.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E. Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
